'''''Tales of the Jedi – The Golden Age of the Sith'' 0''' is a prologue issue of the [[Star Wars Legends|Legends]] [[Star Wars comic books|comic book]] series ''[[Star Wars: Tales of the Jedi – The Golden Age of the Sith]]''. It was written by [[Kevin J. Anderson]], illustrated by [[Chris Gossett]], and published on [[July 31]], [[1996]] by [[Dark Horse Comics]].

==Publisher's summary==
''Five millennia before Luke Skywalker was born &mdash; and 1,000 years before two young Jedi reawakened a long-dormant evil &mdash; the dark power of The Sith held unquestioning rule over the galaxy. For those black-souled, corrupt Jedi, it was a golden age. For the rest of the galaxy, it was a nightmare.''

==Opening crawl==
{{OpeningCrawl
|name=Conquest and Unification
|text=The complete history of the Old
Republic would fill a thousand
libraries. But some events, some
sacrifices, have become legend,
passed from generation to
generation &mdash; the epic of the
Great Hyperspace War, how the
bold explorations of young Gav
and Jori Daragon brought two
galactic empires crashing
together, how Odan-Urr became
a powerful Jedi and eventually a
Master, and how the seven
worlds of the Koros system were
finally united by the wise and
skilled Empress Teta.

Five millennia before the birth of
Luke Skywalker and the fall of
Palpatine's Empire&hellip;

A thousand years before Exar
Kun and Ulic Qel-Droma joined
forces in a sweeping conflagration
known as the Sith War&hellip;

The story begins.}}

==Plot summary==
[[Odan-Urr/Legends|Odan-Urr]], [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] historian on [[Ossus/Legends|Ossus]], has completed his Jedi training. Odan-Urr is interested in ancient lore particularly the history of the [[Sith/Legends|Sith]]. He is familiar with the [[First Great Schism]], the [[Hundred-Year Darkness/Legends|Hundred-Year Darkness]], and the [[Dark Jedi/Legends|Dark Jedi]] [[Exiles]] who established the [[Sith Empire/Legends|Sith Empire]]. Deemed ready, Odan-Urr is sent by his [[Jedi Master/Legends|Master]] [[Ooroo/Legends|Ooroo]] to fight in the [[Empress Teta system/Legends|Koros system's]] [[Unification Wars (Koros)/Legends|Unification Wars]] alongside [[Empress/Legends|Empress]] [[Teta/Legends|Teta]].

On the planet [[Empress Teta/Legends|Cinnagar]] in the [[Empress Teta system/Legends|Koros system]], [[Hok Daragon|Hok]] and his wife [[Timar Daragon]] work as supply runners for the benevolent [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]] [[Aarrba]], who owns a [[Aarrba's Repair Dock|repair dock]]. Their children [[Gav Daragon|Gav]] and [[Jori Daragon|Jori]] want to accompany their parents for a supply run to the [[Kirrek rebels|rebel]]-held planet of [[Kirrek]]. However, Hok refuses since it is too dangerous. Since Aarrba is keeping their ship ''[[Starbreaker 12]]'' as collateral, the couple depart in the ''[[Shadow Runner]]''.

Meanwhile, Odan-Urr meets with his fellow Jedi [[Memit Nadill]], who serves as Empress [[Teta/Legends|Teta's]] Jedi advisor. The Empress has unified six of the seven worlds in the Koros system through mutual commerce and aid. However, the pirates of Kirrek have rebuffed all attempts, and have been raiding ships. The rebels are still besieging their advanced contingent, and have slaughtered fifty Tetan hostages in retaliation for their last rescue-aid.

While Odan-Urr is not a warrior, he proposes using [[Battle meditation/Legends|battle meditation]] to bring about the defeat of the Kirrek-rebels. He and Memit Nadill fight in the final battle against the rebellion on Kirrek. Using Odan-Urr's [[Battle meditation/Legends|battle meditation]], the Jedi are able to sway the tide in their favor and eventually win, but Odan-Urr clearly does not enjoy the experience. However, a desperate rebel fires upon Hok and Timar's ship ''Shadow Runner'', killing them.

Following the surrender of the Kirrek-rebels, Odan-Urr despairs at the deaths of Hok and Timar. However, Memit reassures him that the battle could have been much worse had it not been for his battle meditation.

Back on Cinnagar, Aarrba informs a distraught Gav and Jori of their parents' deaths. Taking pity on the Daragons, Aarrba gives Gav and Jori their parent's ship, the ''Starbreaker 12'', which was previously held as collateral, saying their parents "paid for it in blood."

